{"title_page": "Alassane Ouattara", "text_new": "{{short description|President of the Ivory Coast (2010\u2013present)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Alassane Ouattara\n| image = A. Ouattara.jpg\n| caption = Alassane Ouattara in 2017\n| office = 5th [[List of heads of state of Ivory Coast|President of the Ivory Coast]]\n| vicepresident = [[Daniel Kablan Duncan]] {{small|(Interim)}}\n| primeminister = [[Guillaume Soro]]<br />[[Jeannot Ahoussou-Kouadio]]<br />[[Daniel Kablan Duncan]]<br />[[Amadou Gon Coulibaly]]\n| term_start = 4 December 2010\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Laurent Gbagbo]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[List of heads of government of Ivory Coast|Prime Minister of the Ivory Coast]]\n| president1 = [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]]\n| term_start1 = 7 November 1990\n| term_end1 = 9 December 1993\n| predecessor1 = [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]]\n| successor1 = [[Daniel Kablan Duncan]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1942|1|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dimbokro]], [[French West Africa]]<br />{{small|(present-day [[Ivory Coast|C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]])}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = {{nowrap|[[Democratic Party of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire \u2013 African Democratic Rally|Democratic Party]] {{small|(Before 1994)}}}}<br />[[Rally of the Republicans]] {{small|(1994\u2013present)}}\n| spouse = [[Dominique Folloroux-Ouattara|Dominique Nouvian]] {{small|(1991\u2013present)}}\n| alma_mater = [[Drexel University]]<br />[[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania|University of Pennsylvania]]\n| religion = [[Sunni Islam]] ([[Maliki]])\n| footnotes = *The presidency was disputed between Ouattara and [[Laurent Gbagbo]] from 4 December 2010 to 11 April 2011.\n| blank1 = Religion\n| data1 = [[Islam]]\n| website = [http://www.presidence.ci/ Official Presidential website]\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of Prince Henry|GColIH]]\n}}\n\n'''Alassane Dramane Ouattara''' ({{IPA-fr|alasan wata\u0281a|-|En-us-Alassane Ouattara from Ivory Coast pronunciation (Voice of America).ogg}}; born 1 January 1942) is an Ivorian politician who has been [[President of Ivory Coast]] (C\u00f4te d'Ivoire) since 2010. An economist by profession, Ouattara worked for the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF)<ref name=\"BBC-Online\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12934834 \"Ivory Coast's Alassane Ouattara in profile\"], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 11 April 2011.</ref> and the [[Central Bank of West African States]] ({{lang-fr|Banque Centrale des Etats de l'Afrique de l'Ouest}}, BCEAO), and he was the [[Prime Minister of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] from November 1990 to December 1993, appointed to that post by President [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]].<ref name=IMF>{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/np/omd/bios/Ado.htm |title=Profile at IMF website |accessdate=2011-04-11 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221095339/http://www.imf.org/external/np/omd/bios/Ado.htm |archivedate=21 December 2005 |df=dmy }}, 12 December 2005.</ref><ref name=ADO>[http://www.ado.ci/ CV at Ouattara's website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109032129/http://www.ado.ci/ |date=9 November 2007 }} {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/a-tale-of-2-presidents-1.987162 |title=A tale of 2 presidents | work=CBC News | date=25 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailytrust.dailytrust.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10022:gbagbo-preventing-ecowas-military-misadventure-in-cote-divoire&catid=7:opinion&Itemid=12 |title=Gbagbo: Preventing ECOWAS military misadventure in Cote d\u2019Ivoire |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708221638/http://dailytrust.dailytrust.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10022%3Agbagbo-preventing-ecowas-military-misadventure-in-cote-divoire&catid=7%3Aopinion&Itemid=12 |archivedate=8 July 2011 }}</ref> Ouattara became the President of the [[Rally of the Republicans]] (RDR), an Ivorian political party, in 1999.\n\n==Early life==\nOuattara was born on 1 January 1942<ref name=IMF/><ref name=ADO/> in [[Dimbokro]] in [[French West Africa]].<ref>Laing, Aislinn, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/cotedivoire/8432085/Ivory-Coast-Alassane-Ouattara-profile.html \"Ivory Coast: Alassane Ouattara profile\"], ''[[Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', 6 April 2011.</ref> He is a descendant on his father's side of the Muslim rulers of [[Burkina Faso]], then part of the [[Kong Empire]] \u2014 also known as the Wattara (Ouattarra) Empire. Ouattara himself is of Muslim background.<ref name=\"kong\">[http://www.economist.com/node/18587205 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire's new president - The king of Kong - Alassane Ouattara takes charge but can he keep the peace?\"] He studied at the High School Zinda Kabor\u00e9 in Ouaga(Burkina Faso)  ''[[The Economist]]'', 20 April 2011.</ref> He received a [[bachelor of science]] degree in 1965 from the [[Drexel Institute of Technology]], which is now called [[Drexel University]], in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=IMF/> Ouattara then obtained both his master's degree in economics in 1967 and a PhD in economics in 1972 from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=IMF/>\n\nIn 1991, Ouattara was married to [[Dominique Folloroux-Ouattara|Dominique Nouvian]], a French Catholic businesswoman of Jewish descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/15/alassane-ouattara-ivory-coast|title=Alassane Ouattara reaches summit but has more mountains to climb|last=Smith|first=David|date=2011-04-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Their wedding ceremony was held in the town hall of the prestigious [[16th arrondissement of Paris]].\n\n==Career at financial institutions==\nHe was an economist for the [[International Monetary Fund]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=ADO/> from 1968 to 1973, and afterwards he was the ''Charg\u00e9 de Mission'' in Paris of the Banque Centrale des Etats de l\u2019Afrique de l\u2019Ouest (West African Central Bank) from 1973 to 1975.<ref name=IMF/><ref name=ADO/> With the BCEAO, he was then Special Advisor to the Governor and Director of Research from February 1975 to December 1982 and Vice Governor from January 1983 to October 1984. From November 1984 to October 1988 he was Director of the African Department at the IMF, and in May 1987 he additionally became Counsellor to the Managing Director at the IMF.<ref name=ADO/> On 28 October 1988 he was appointed as Governor of the BCEAO, and he was sworn in on 22 December 1988.<ref name=BCEAO>[http://www.bceao.int/internet/bcweb.nsf/pages/ubc2 \"Basic texts and milestones\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927051630/http://www.bceao.int/internet/bcweb.nsf/pages/ubc2 |date=27 September 2007 }}, bceao.int.</ref> Ouattara has a reputation as a hard-worker, keen on transparency and good governance.<ref name=\"BBC-Online\"/>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n===Prime Minister===\nIn April 1990, the IMF under the Structural Adjustment Program forced the Ivorian President, [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]], to accept Ouattara as Chairman of the Inter-ministerial Committee for Coordination of the Stabilization and Economic Recovery Programme of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire.  While holding that position, Ouattara also remained in his post as BCEAO Governor. He subsequently became Prime Minister of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire on 7 November 1990, still under the IMF imposition,<ref name=ADO/><ref name=BCEAO/> after which [[Charles Konan Banny]] replaced him as Interim BCEAO Governor.<ref name=BCEAO/>\n\nWhile serving as Prime Minister, Ouattara also tried, illegally and against the constitution, to carry out presidential duties for a total of 18 months, including the period from March to December 1993, when Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny was ill.<ref>[http://www.ado.ci/templates/defaulte525.html?adosection={105ABD71-9AD5-4894-B662-8D9ADFB99653}&adolanguage={3C80098E-4443-4536-85EB-0499FB0C268E}&view={9905A651-901F-4DEC-9F81-5654F337C265} \"Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny et ADO: du comit\u00e9 interminist\u00e9riel \u00e0 la Primature\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ado.ci {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny died on 7 December 1993, and Ouattara announced his death to the nation, saying that \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire is orphaned\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927013500/http://www.ado.ci/templates/defaultac6c.html?adosection%3D%7B105ABD71%2D9AD5%2D4894%2DB662%2D8D9ADFB99653%7D%26adolanguage%3D%7B3C80098E%2D4443%2D4536%2D85EB%2D0499FB0C268E%7D%26view%3D%7B5338D065%2DD99B%2D45AA%2DBBED%2D14822716BE8A%7D \"D\u00e9c\u00e8s du Pr\u00e9sident F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny\"], ado.ci {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>\"African Leader Dies\", ''[[Newsday]]'', 8 December 1993.</ref> A brief power struggle ensued between Ouattara and [[Henri Konan B\u00e9di\u00e9]], the President of the National Assembly, over the presidential succession in total disregard for the constitution that clearly gave Bedi\u00e9 the legal right to lead the country if Houphouet became unfit. B\u00e9di\u00e9 prevailed and Ouattara resigned as Prime Minister on 9 December.<ref name=San>\"Prime minister decides to quit\", Associated Press (''San Antonio Express-News''), 10 December 1993.</ref> Ouattara then returned to the IMF as Deputy Managing Director, holding that post from 1 July 1994,<ref name=IMF/><ref name=ADO/> to 31 July 1999.<ref name=ADO/>\n\n===1995 election===\nPrior to the [[1995 Ivorian presidential election|October 1995 presidential election]], the [[National Assembly of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] approved an electoral code that barred candidates if either of their parents were of a foreign nationality and if they had not lived in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire for the preceding five years. It was widely thought these provisions were aimed at Ouattara. Owing to his duties with the IMF, he had not resided in the country since 1990. Also, his father was rumoured to have been born in [[Burkina Faso]].  The [[Rally of the Republicans]] (RDR), an opposition party formed as a split from the ruling [[Democratic Party of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] (PDCI) in 1994, sought for Ouattara to be its presidential candidate. In late June 1995, RDR Secretary-General [[Dj\u00e9ni Kobina]] met with Ouattara, at which time, according to Kobina, Ouattara said: \"I'm ready to join you.\"<ref name=Mundt>{{Cite book |last=Mundt |first=Robert J. |chapter=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Continuity and Change in a Semi-Democracy |year=1997 |title=Political Reform in Francophone Africa |editor1-last=Clark |editor1-first=John Frank |editor2-last=Gardinier |editor2-first=David E. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/politicalreformi0000unse/page/194 194\u2013197] |location=Boulder |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=0-8133-2785-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/politicalreformi0000unse/page/194 }}</ref> The party nominated Ouattara as its presidential candidate on 3 July 1995<ref>\"Jul 1995 - Selection of Ouattara as RDR presidential candidate\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', Volume 41, July 1995 Cote d'Ivoire, p. 40630.</ref> at its first ordinary congress.<ref>Brahima, Coulibaly, [http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200707280095.html \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Organisation du 2\u00e8me congr\u00e8s ordinaire du Rdr, des cadres manoeuvrent pour le report\"], ''Nord-Sud'' (allAfrica.com), 27 July 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> The government would not change the electoral code, however,<ref name=Mundt/> and Ouattara declined the nomination.<ref>[http://www.ado.ci/templates/default2718.html?adosection={105ABD71-9AD5-4894-B662-8D9ADFB99653}&adolanguage={3C80098E-4443-4536-85EB-0499FB0C268E}&view={F657D00D-3F42-49EC-A1B4-99E85152D467} \"ADO est \u00e9lu Pr\u00e9sident du RDR, le 1er Ao\u00fbt 1999\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ado.ci {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>\"Oct 1995 - Presidential elections\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', Volume 41, October 1995 Cote d'Ivoire, p. 40759.</ref> The RDR [[election boycott|boycotted the election]], along with the [[Ivorian Popular Front]] (FPI) of [[Laurent Gbagbo]], leaving the PDCI's candidate, incumbent president [[Henri Konan B\u00e9di\u00e9]], to win an easy victory.<ref name=Mundt/>\n\n===President of the RDR===\nWhile serving as Deputy Managing Director at the IMF, in March 1998 Ouattara expressed his intention to return to C\u00f4te d'Ivoire and take part in politics again.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/monitoring/71724.stm \"Ivorian ex-premier to quit IMF for return to politics\"], ''BBC News Online'', 30 March 1998.</ref> After leaving the IMF in July 1999, he was elected President of the RDR on 1 August 1999 at an extraordinary congress of the party,<ref name=ADOBio>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927013439/http://www.ado.ci/templates/defaultb395.html?adosection=%7BBC4C21B3-2509-40EA-86A3- Biography at Ouattara's website] {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> as well as being chosen as its candidate for the next presidential election.<ref>\"Ivorian opposition elects former premier as presidential candidate\", ''[[Associated Press]]'', 1 August 1999.</ref> He said he was eligible to stand in the election, pointing to documents he said demonstrated that he and his parents were of Ivorian birth.\n\nHe was accused of forging these papers, however, and an investigation was begun.<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=9118 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Police arrest scores outside politician's home\"], ''[[IRIN]]'', 15 September 1999.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/454674.stm \"Ivory Coast opposition leader under investigation\"], ''BBC News Online'', 22 September 1999.</ref> President B\u00e9di\u00e9 described Ouattara as a [[Demographics of Burkina Faso|Burkinab\u00e9]] and said that Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny \"wanted Alassane Ouattara to concern himself only with the economy\".<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=54493 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Former political foes strike pact to oust Gbagbo\"], ''IRIN'', 18 May 2005.</ref> Ouattara's nationality certificate, issued in late September 1999,<ref name=Annul>\"Cote d'Ivoire: Court annuls presidential candidate's nationality certificate\", ''[[Agence France Presse|AFP]]'', 27 October 1999.</ref> was annulled by a court on 27 October.<ref name=Annul/><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/493013.stm \"Opposition leader blasts 'undemocratic' government\"], ''BBC News Online'', 29 October 1999.</ref> An arrest warrant for Ouattara was issued on 29 November, although he was out of the country at the time; he nevertheless said that he would return by late December.<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=11130 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Arrest warrant issued for opposition politician\"], ''IRIN'', 9 December 1999.</ref>\n\nOn 24 December, [[1999 Ivorian coup d'\u00e9tat|the military seized power]], ousting B\u00e9di\u00e9. Ouattara returned to C\u00f4te d'Ivoire after three months in France on 29 December, hailing B\u00e9di\u00e9's ouster as \"not a coup d'\u00e9tat\", but \"a revolution supported by all the Ivorian people\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/582403.stm \"Ivory Coast coup a 'popular revolution'\"],<!--(it worthy to note the coincidence)--> ''BBC News Online'', 29 December 1999.</ref><ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=11520 \"COTE D'IVOIRE: Former Prime Minister returns home\"], ''IRIN'', 4 January 2000.</ref>\n\nA new constitution, approved by referendum in July 2000, controversially barred presidential candidates unless both of their parents were Ivorian,<ref>\"Jul 2000 \u2013 Referendum on new constitution\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', Volume 46, July 2000 Cote d'Ivoire, p. 43661.</ref> and Ouattara was disqualified from the [[2000 Ivorian presidential election|2000 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Cyril K. |last=Daddieh |year=2001 |title=Elections and Ethnic Violence in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: The Unfinished Business of Succession and Democratic Transition |journal=[[African Issues]] |volume=29 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=14\u201319 |doi=10.2307/1167104 }}</ref> The issues surrounding this were major factors in the [[First Ivorian Civil War]], which broke out in 2002.\n\nWhen asked in an interview about Ouattara's nationality, Burkinab\u00e9 President [[Blaise Compaor\u00e9]] responded, \"For us things are simple: he does not come from Burkina Faso, neither by birth, marriage, or naturalization. This man has been Prime Minister of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire.\"\n\nPresident Gbagbo affirmed on 6 August 2007 that Ouattara could stand in the next Ivorian presidential election.<ref>[https://www.humanite.fr/2007-08-08_International_Dans-l-actualite \"La pr\u00e9sidentielle envisag\u00e9e par Gbagbo pour fin 2007\"], ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'', 8 August 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Ouattara was designated as the RDR's presidential candidate at its Second Ordinary Congress on 1\u20133 February 2008; he was also re-elected as President of the RDR for another five years. At the congress, he invited the former rebel [[Forces Nouvelles de C\u00f4te d'Ivoire|New Forces]], from whom he had previously distanced himself, to team up with the RDR for the election.<ref name=Pret>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/pays/cote_ivoire/article_depeche.asp?art_cle=AFP35428alassselleb0 \"Alassane Ouattara pr\u00eat \u00e0 s'associer aux ex-rebelles\"], AFP, 3 February 2008.</ref>\n\nAt the time, Ouattara said publicly that he did not believe Gbagbo would organize transparent and fair elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=39769 |title=\"We Don't Believe Gbagbo Will Organise Transparent Elections\" Michael Deibert interviews Alassane Ouattara |publisher=Inter Press Service |date=23 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826181445/http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=39769 |archivedate=26 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe RDR and the PDCI are both members of the Rally of Houphou\u00ebtistes, and while Ouattara and B\u00e9di\u00e9 ran separately in the first round, each agreed to support the other if only one of them made it into a potential second round.<ref name=Pret/>\n\n===2010 presidential election and aftermath===\n[[File:Alassane Ouattara UNESCO 09-2011.jpg|thumb|right|Ouattara at [[UNESCO]] in September 2011]]\n{{update|date=December 2013}}<!--http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2013/12/ivory-coast-targets-gbagbo-followers-ghana-201312252716257571.html-->\n{{main|2010 Ivorian presidential election|2010\u20132011 Ivorian crisis}}\n\nThe presidential elections that should have been organized in 2005 were postponed until November 2010. The preliminary results announced independently by the president of the Electoral Commission from the headquarters of Ouattara due to concern about fraud in that commission.{{clarify|date=February 2018}} They showed a loss for Gbagbo in favour of former prime minister Alassane Ouattara.<ref name=Thousands26>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12079552|accessdate=26 December 2010|publisher= BBC News |title= Thousands flee Ivory Coast for Liberia amid poll crisis|date=26 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe ruling FPI contested the results before the [[Constitutional Council (Ivory Coast)|Constitutional Council]], charging massive fraud in the northern departments controlled by the rebels of the New Forces. These charges were contradicted by United Nations observers (unlike African Union observers). The report of the results led to severe tension and violent incidents. The Constitutional Council, which consisted of Gbagbo supporters, declared the results of seven northern departments unlawful and that Gbagbo had won the elections with 51% of the vote \u2013 instead of Ouattara winning with 54%, as reported by the Electoral Commission.<ref name=Thousands26 /> After the inauguration of Gbagbo, Ouattara\u2014who was recognized as the winner by most countries and the United Nations\u2014organized an alternative inauguration. These events raised fears of a resurgence of the civil war; thousands of refugees fled the country.<ref name=Thousands26 />\n\nThe [[African Union]] sent [[Thabo Mbeki]], former President of South Africa, to mediate the conflict. The [[United Nations Security Council]] adopted a resolution recognising Alassane Ouattara as winner of the elections, based on the position of the [[Economic Community of West African States]], which suspended Ivory Coast from all its decision-making bodies<ref>[http://news.ecowas.int/presseshow.php?nb=188&lang=en&annee=2010 \"Final Communique on the Extraordinary Session of the Authority of Heads of State and Government on Cote D\u2019Ivoire\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503190625/http://news.ecowas.int/presseshow.php?nb=188&lang=en&annee=2010 |date=3 May 2011 }}, Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), 7 December 2010.</ref> while the African Union also suspended the country's membership.<ref>[http://www.africa-union.org/root/au/Conferences/2010/december/Communiqu%C3%A9%20of%20the%20252nd.pdf \"Communique of the 252nd Meeting of the Peace and Security Council\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206013356/http://www.africa-union.org/root/au/Conferences/2010/december/Communiqu%C3%A9%20of%20the%20252nd.pdf |date= 6 February 2011 }}, African Union, 9 December 2010.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, a colonel of the Ivory Coast armed forces, Nguessan Yao, was arrested in New York in a year-long [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] operation charged with procuring and illegal export of weapons and munitions: 4,000 [[9 mm]] handguns, 200,000 rounds of ammunition, and 50,000 tear-gas grenades, in violation of a UN embargo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/ice-deports-ivory-coast-army-colonel-convicted-arms-trafficking |date=November 30, 2012 |title=ICE deports Ivory Coast army colonel convicted of arms trafficking |publisher=Immigration and Customs Enforcement}}</ref> Several other Ivory Coast officers were released because they had diplomatic passports. His accomplice, Michael Barry Shor, an international trader, was located in [[Virginia (state)|Virginia]].<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2010/09/21/FBI-nabbed-colonel-on-official-business/UPI-16431285082800/ \"FBI nabbed colonel on official business\"], UPI, 21 September 2010.</ref><ref>[https://cases.justia.com/federal/appellate-courts/ca9/13-10642/13-10642-2015-12-18.pdf?ts=1450472514 United States Court of Appeals Memorandum], 18 December 2015.</ref>\n\nThe 2010 presidential election led to the [[2010\u20132011 Ivorian crisis]] and the Second Ivorian Civil War. International organizations reported numerous human-rights violations by both sides. In the city of [[Du\u00e9kou\u00e9]], hundreds of people were killed. In nearby [[Blol\u00e9quin]], dozens were killed.<ref>{{cite web|date=27 April 2011|last=DiCampo|first=Peter|title= An Uncertain Future| url= http://pulitzercenter.org/articles/ivory-coast-gbagbo-election-violence|work=Ivory Coast: Elections Turn to War |publisher= Pulitzer Center}}</ref> UN and French forces took military action against Gbagbo.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ivory-coast-strongman-arrested-after-french-forces-intervene/2011/04/11/AFOBaeKD_story.html |title= Ivory Coast strongman arrested after French forces intervene |first1= Colum |last1= Lynch |first2= William |last2= Branigin |work= [[Washington Post]] |date=11 April 2011 |accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref> Gbagbo was taken into custody after a raid into his residence on 11 April 2011. The country was severely damaged by the war, and observers say it will be a challenge for Ouattara to rebuild the economy and reunite Ivorians.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/apr/11/ivory-coast-gbagbo-ouattara-economic-crisis|title=The war is over \u2014 but Ouattara's struggle has barely begun|work= The Guardian|date=11 April 2011|first= Thalia |last= Griffiths|location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe developments in the country were welcomed by world leaders. U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] applauded news of the developments in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire and CNN quoted U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton as saying Gbagbo's capture \"sends a strong signal to dictators and tyrants.... They may not disregard the voice of their own people\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/11/ivory.coast.crisis/?hpt=T2 |title=Obama, Clinton welcome new developments |work=CNN |date=11 April 2011 |accessdate=12 April 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110412034017/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/11/ivory.coast.crisis/?hpt=T2| archivedate= 12 April 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==== 2012 Marriage Law row ====\nIn a controversial move in November 2012, President Ouattara sacked his government in a row over a new marriage law that would make wives joint heads of the household. His own party supported the changes but the elements of the ruling coalition resisted, with the strongest opposition coming from the Democratic Party of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire.<ref>{{Citation|title=Ouattara dissolves Ivorian government over marriage law|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20322103|year=2012|publication-place=[[United Kingdom]]|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=16 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Second term, 2015\u2013present===\n{{Main|2015 Ivorian presidential election}}\nAlassan Ouattara won a second five-year term in 2015 with almost 84% of the vote. With 2,118,229 votes, or 83.66% of votes cast, and a 54.63% turnout, Ouattara's victory was a landslide compared to the 50% required to avoid a run-off and the 9% of his closest rival, FPI leader [[Pascal Affi N'Guessan]].\n\nAt the RDR's Third Ordinary Congress on 9&ndash;10 September 2017, it was expected that Ouattara would be elected as President of the RDR, but he instead proposed [[Henriette Diabat\u00e9]] for the post, and she was duly elected by acclamation.<ref>Sylvestre-Treiner, Anna, [http://www.jeuneafrique.com/473092/politique/cote-divoire-henriette-diabate-nouvelle-presidente-du-rdr-le-parti-dalassane-ouattara/ \"C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire : Alassane Ouattara choisit Henriette Dagri Diabat\u00e9 pour pr\u00e9sider son parti\"], ''Jeune Afrique'', 10 September 2017 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n\n==== Foreign Honours ====\n\n* [[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Grand Collar BAR.png|alt=|80x80px]] Grand Collar of the [[Order of Prince Henry]], [[Portugal]] (September 12, 2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Africa|Biography|Politics}}\n{{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050206052408/http://alassaneouattara.com/ Alassane Ouattara.com] Political Web site from Ouattara's circle of influence.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of government of Ivory Coast|Prime Minister of the Ivory Coast]]|years=1990\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Daniel Kablan Duncan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Laurent Gbagbo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of state of Ivory Coast|President of the Ivory Coast]]|years=2010\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Goodluck Jonathan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairperson of the [[Economic Community of West African States]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Dramani Mahama]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{IvorianPresidents}}\n{{IvorianPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouattara, Alassane}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Drexel University alumni]]\n[[Category:Heads of government of Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Ivorian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Ivorian democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Ivorian economists]]\n[[Category:Ivorian people of Burkinab\u00e9 descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dimbokro]]\n[[Category:Rally of the Republicans politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Order of Benin]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|President of the Ivory Coast (2010-present)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Alassane Ouattara\n| image = A. Ouattara.jpg\n| caption = Alassane Ouattara in 2017\n| office = 5th [[List of heads of state of Ivory Coast|President of the Ivory Coast]]\n| vicepresident = [[Daniel Kablan Duncan]] {{small|(Interim)}}\n| primeminister = [[Guillaume Soro]]<br />[[Jeannot Ahoussou-Kouadio]]<br />[[Daniel Kablan Duncan]]<br />[[Amadou Gon Coulibaly]]\n| term_start = 4 December 2010\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Laurent Gbagbo]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[List of heads of government of Ivory Coast|Prime Minister of the Ivory Coast]]\n| president1 = [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]]\n| term_start1 = 7 November 1990\n| term_end1 = 9 December 1993\n| predecessor1 = [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]]\n| successor1 = [[Daniel Kablan Duncan]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1942|1|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dimbokro]], [[French West Africa]]<br />{{small|(present-day [[Ivory Coast|C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]])}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = {{nowrap|[[Democratic Party of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire \u2013 African Democratic Rally|Democratic Party]] {{small|(Before 1994)}}}}<br />[[Rally of the Republicans]] {{small|(1994\u2013present)}}\n| spouse = [[Dominique Folloroux-Ouattara|Dominique Nouvian]] {{small|(1991\u2013present)}}\n| alma_mater = [[Drexel University]]<br />[[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania|University of Pennsylvania]]\n| religion = [[Sunni Islam]] ([[Maliki]])\n| footnotes = *The presidency was disputed between Ouattara and [[Laurent Gbagbo]] from 4 December 2010 to 11 April 2011.\n| blank1 = Religion\n| data1 = [[Islam]]\n| website = [http://www.presidence.ci/ Official Presidential website]\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of Prince Henry|GColIH]]\n}}\n\n'''Alassane Dramane Ouattara''' ({{IPA-fr|alasan wata\u0281a|-|En-us-Alassane Ouattara from Ivory Coast pronunciation (Voice of America).ogg}}; born 1 January 1942) is an Ivorian politician who has been [[President of Ivory Coast]] (C\u00f4te d'Ivoire) since 2010. An economist by profession, Ouattara worked for the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF)<ref name=\"BBC-Online\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12934834 \"Ivory Coast's Alassane Ouattara in profile\"], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 11 April 2011.</ref> and the [[Central Bank of West African States]] ({{lang-fr|Banque Centrale des Etats de l'Afrique de l'Ouest}}, BCEAO), and he was the [[Prime Minister of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] from November 1990 to December 1993, appointed to that post by President [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]].<ref name=IMF>{{cite web|url=http://www.imf.org/external/np/omd/bios/Ado.htm |title=Profile at IMF website |accessdate=2011-04-11 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051221095339/http://www.imf.org/external/np/omd/bios/Ado.htm |archivedate=21 December 2005 |df=dmy }}, 12 December 2005.</ref><ref name=ADO>[http://www.ado.ci/ CV at Ouattara's website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109032129/http://www.ado.ci/ |date=9 November 2007 }} {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/a-tale-of-2-presidents-1.987162 |title=A tale of 2 presidents | work=CBC News | date=25 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailytrust.dailytrust.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10022:gbagbo-preventing-ecowas-military-misadventure-in-cote-divoire&catid=7:opinion&Itemid=12 |title=Gbagbo: Preventing ECOWAS military misadventure in Cote d\u2019Ivoire |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708221638/http://dailytrust.dailytrust.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10022%3Agbagbo-preventing-ecowas-military-misadventure-in-cote-divoire&catid=7%3Aopinion&Itemid=12 |archivedate=8 July 2011 }}</ref> Ouattara became the President of the [[Rally of the Republicans]] (RDR), an Ivorian political party, in 1999.\n\n==Early life==\nOuattara was born on 1 January 1942<ref name=IMF/><ref name=ADO/> in [[Dimbokro]] in [[French West Africa]].<ref>Laing, Aislinn, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/cotedivoire/8432085/Ivory-Coast-Alassane-Ouattara-profile.html \"Ivory Coast: Alassane Ouattara profile\"], ''[[Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', 6 April 2011.</ref> He is a descendant on his father's side of the Muslim rulers of [[Burkina Faso]], then part of the [[Kong Empire]] \u2014 also known as the Wattara (Ouattarra) Empire. Ouattara himself is of Muslim background.<ref name=\"kong\">[http://www.economist.com/node/18587205 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire's new president - The king of Kong - Alassane Ouattara takes charge but can he keep the peace?\"] He studied at the High School Zinda Kabor\u00e9 in Ouaga(Burkina Faso)  ''[[The Economist]]'', 20 April 2011.</ref> He received a [[bachelor of science]] degree in 1965 from the [[Drexel Institute of Technology]], which is now called [[Drexel University]], in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=IMF/> Ouattara then obtained both his master's degree in economics in 1967 and a PhD in economics in 1972 from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=IMF/>\n\nIn 1991, Ouattara was married to [[Dominique Folloroux-Ouattara|Dominique Nouvian]], a French Catholic businesswoman of Jewish descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/15/alassane-ouattara-ivory-coast|title=Alassane Ouattara reaches summit but has more mountains to climb|last=Smith|first=David|date=2011-04-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Their wedding ceremony was held in the town hall of the prestigious [[16th arrondissement of Paris]].\n\n==Career at financial institutions==\nHe was an economist for the [[International Monetary Fund]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=ADO/> from 1968 to 1973, and afterwards he was the ''Charg\u00e9 de Mission'' in Paris of the Banque Centrale des Etats de l\u2019Afrique de l\u2019Ouest (West African Central Bank) from 1973 to 1975.<ref name=IMF/><ref name=ADO/> With the BCEAO, he was then Special Advisor to the Governor and Director of Research from February 1975 to December 1982 and Vice Governor from January 1983 to October 1984. From November 1984 to October 1988 he was Director of the African Department at the IMF, and in May 1987 he additionally became Counsellor to the Managing Director at the IMF.<ref name=ADO/> On 28 October 1988 he was appointed as Governor of the BCEAO, and he was sworn in on 22 December 1988.<ref name=BCEAO>[http://www.bceao.int/internet/bcweb.nsf/pages/ubc2 \"Basic texts and milestones\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927051630/http://www.bceao.int/internet/bcweb.nsf/pages/ubc2 |date=27 September 2007 }}, bceao.int.</ref> Ouattara has a reputation as a hard-worker, keen on transparency and good governance.<ref name=\"BBC-Online\"/>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n===Prime Minister===\nIn April 1990, the IMF under the Structural Adjustment Program forced the Ivorian President, [[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]], to accept Ouattara as Chairman of the Inter-ministerial Committee for Coordination of the Stabilization and Economic Recovery Programme of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire.  While holding that position, Ouattara also remained in his post as BCEAO Governor. He subsequently became Prime Minister of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire on 7 November 1990, still under the IMF imposition,<ref name=ADO/><ref name=BCEAO/> after which [[Charles Konan Banny]] replaced him as Interim BCEAO Governor.<ref name=BCEAO/>\n\nWhile serving as Prime Minister, Ouattara also tried, illegally and against the constitution, to carry out presidential duties for a total of 18 months, including the period from March to December 1993, when Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny was ill.<ref>[http://www.ado.ci/templates/defaulte525.html?adosection={105ABD71-9AD5-4894-B662-8D9ADFB99653}&adolanguage={3C80098E-4443-4536-85EB-0499FB0C268E}&view={9905A651-901F-4DEC-9F81-5654F337C265} \"Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny et ADO: du comit\u00e9 interminist\u00e9riel \u00e0 la Primature\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ado.ci {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny died on 7 December 1993, and Ouattara announced his death to the nation, saying that \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire is orphaned\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927013500/http://www.ado.ci/templates/defaultac6c.html?adosection%3D%7B105ABD71%2D9AD5%2D4894%2DB662%2D8D9ADFB99653%7D%26adolanguage%3D%7B3C80098E%2D4443%2D4536%2D85EB%2D0499FB0C268E%7D%26view%3D%7B5338D065%2DD99B%2D45AA%2DBBED%2D14822716BE8A%7D \"D\u00e9c\u00e8s du Pr\u00e9sident F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny\"], ado.ci {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>\"African Leader Dies\", ''[[Newsday]]'', 8 December 1993.</ref> A brief power struggle ensued between Ouattara and [[Henri Konan B\u00e9di\u00e9]], the President of the National Assembly, over the presidential succession in total disregard for the constitution that clearly gave Bedi\u00e9 the legal right to lead the country if Houphouet became unfit. B\u00e9di\u00e9 prevailed and Ouattara resigned as Prime Minister on 9 December.<ref name=San>\"Prime minister decides to quit\", Associated Press (''San Antonio Express-News''), 10 December 1993.</ref> Ouattara then returned to the IMF as Deputy Managing Director, holding that post from 1 July 1994,<ref name=IMF/><ref name=ADO/> to 31 July 1999.<ref name=ADO/>\n\n===1995 election===\nPrior to the [[1995 Ivorian presidential election|October 1995 presidential election]], the [[National Assembly of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] approved an electoral code that barred candidates if either of their parents were of a foreign nationality and if they had not lived in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire for the preceding five years. It was widely thought these provisions were aimed at Ouattara. Owing to his duties with the IMF, he had not resided in the country since 1990. Also, his father was rumoured to have been born in [[Burkina Faso]].  The [[Rally of the Republicans]] (RDR), an opposition party formed as a split from the ruling [[Democratic Party of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] (PDCI) in 1994, sought for Ouattara to be its presidential candidate. In late June 1995, RDR Secretary-General [[Dj\u00e9ni Kobina]] met with Ouattara, at which time, according to Kobina, Ouattara said: \"I'm ready to join you.\"<ref name=Mundt>{{Cite book |last=Mundt |first=Robert J. |chapter=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Continuity and Change in a Semi-Democracy |year=1997 |title=Political Reform in Francophone Africa |editor1-last=Clark |editor1-first=John Frank |editor2-last=Gardinier |editor2-first=David E. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/politicalreformi0000unse/page/194 194\u2013197] |location=Boulder |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=0-8133-2785-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/politicalreformi0000unse/page/194 }}</ref> The party nominated Ouattara as its presidential candidate on 3 July 1995<ref>\"Jul 1995 - Selection of Ouattara as RDR presidential candidate\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', Volume 41, July 1995 Cote d'Ivoire, p. 40630.</ref> at its first ordinary congress.<ref>Brahima, Coulibaly, [http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200707280095.html \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Organisation du 2\u00e8me congr\u00e8s ordinaire du Rdr, des cadres manoeuvrent pour le report\"], ''Nord-Sud'' (allAfrica.com), 27 July 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> The government would not change the electoral code, however,<ref name=Mundt/> and Ouattara declined the nomination.<ref>[http://www.ado.ci/templates/default2718.html?adosection={105ABD71-9AD5-4894-B662-8D9ADFB99653}&adolanguage={3C80098E-4443-4536-85EB-0499FB0C268E}&view={F657D00D-3F42-49EC-A1B4-99E85152D467} \"ADO est \u00e9lu Pr\u00e9sident du RDR, le 1er Ao\u00fbt 1999\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ado.ci {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>\"Oct 1995 - Presidential elections\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', Volume 41, October 1995 Cote d'Ivoire, p. 40759.</ref> The RDR [[election boycott|boycotted the election]], along with the [[Ivorian Popular Front]] (FPI) of [[Laurent Gbagbo]], leaving the PDCI's candidate, incumbent president [[Henri Konan B\u00e9di\u00e9]], to win an easy victory.<ref name=Mundt/>\n\n===President of the RDR===\nWhile serving as Deputy Managing Director at the IMF, in March 1998 Ouattara expressed his intention to return to C\u00f4te d'Ivoire and take part in politics again.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/monitoring/71724.stm \"Ivorian ex-premier to quit IMF for return to politics\"], ''BBC News Online'', 30 March 1998.</ref> After leaving the IMF in July 1999, he was elected President of the RDR on 1 August 1999 at an extraordinary congress of the party,<ref name=ADOBio>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927013439/http://www.ado.ci/templates/defaultb395.html?adosection=%7BBC4C21B3-2509-40EA-86A3- Biography at Ouattara's website] {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> as well as being chosen as its candidate for the next presidential election.<ref>\"Ivorian opposition elects former premier as presidential candidate\", ''[[Associated Press]]'', 1 August 1999.</ref> He said he was eligible to stand in the election, pointing to documents he said demonstrated that he and his parents were of Ivorian birth.\n\nHe was accused of forging these papers, however, and an investigation was begun.<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=9118 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Police arrest scores outside politician's home\"], ''[[IRIN]]'', 15 September 1999.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/454674.stm \"Ivory Coast opposition leader under investigation\"], ''BBC News Online'', 22 September 1999.</ref> President B\u00e9di\u00e9 described Ouattara as a [[Demographics of Burkina Faso|Burkinab\u00e9]] and said that Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny \"wanted Alassane Ouattara to concern himself only with the economy\".<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=54493 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Former political foes strike pact to oust Gbagbo\"], ''IRIN'', 18 May 2005.</ref> Ouattara's nationality certificate, issued in late September 1999,<ref name=Annul>\"Cote d'Ivoire: Court annuls presidential candidate's nationality certificate\", ''[[Agence France Presse|AFP]]'', 27 October 1999.</ref> was annulled by a court on 27 October.<ref name=Annul/><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/493013.stm \"Opposition leader blasts 'undemocratic' government\"], ''BBC News Online'', 29 October 1999.</ref> An arrest warrant for Ouattara was issued on 29 November, although he was out of the country at the time; he nevertheless said that he would return by late December.<ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=11130 \"C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: Arrest warrant issued for opposition politician\"], ''IRIN'', 9 December 1999.</ref>\n\nOn 24 December, [[1999 Ivorian coup d'\u00e9tat|the military seized power]], ousting B\u00e9di\u00e9. Ouattara returned to C\u00f4te d'Ivoire after three months in France on 29 December, hailing B\u00e9di\u00e9's ouster as \"not a coup d'\u00e9tat\", but \"a revolution supported by all the Ivorian people\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/582403.stm \"Ivory Coast coup a 'popular revolution'\"],<!--(it worthy to note the coincidence)--> ''BBC News Online'', 29 December 1999.</ref><ref>[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=11520 \"COTE D'IVOIRE: Former Prime Minister returns home\"], ''IRIN'', 4 January 2000.</ref>\n\nA new constitution, approved by referendum in July 2000, controversially barred presidential candidates unless both of their parents were Ivorian,<ref>\"Jul 2000 \u2013 Referendum on new constitution\", ''Keesing's Record of World Events'', Volume 46, July 2000 Cote d'Ivoire, p. 43661.</ref> and Ouattara was disqualified from the [[2000 Ivorian presidential election|2000 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Cyril K. |last=Daddieh |year=2001 |title=Elections and Ethnic Violence in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire: The Unfinished Business of Succession and Democratic Transition |journal=[[African Issues]] |volume=29 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=14\u201319 |doi=10.2307/1167104 }}</ref> The issues surrounding this were major factors in the [[First Ivorian Civil War]], which broke out in 2002.\n\nWhen asked in an interview about Ouattara's nationality, Burkinab\u00e9 President [[Blaise Compaor\u00e9]] responded, \"For us things are simple: he does not come from Burkina Faso, neither by birth, marriage, or naturalization. This man has been Prime Minister of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire.\"\n\nPresident Gbagbo affirmed on 6 August 2007 that Ouattara could stand in the next Ivorian presidential election.<ref>[https://www.humanite.fr/2007-08-08_International_Dans-l-actualite \"La pr\u00e9sidentielle envisag\u00e9e par Gbagbo pour fin 2007\"], ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'', 8 August 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> Ouattara was designated as the RDR's presidential candidate at its Second Ordinary Congress on 1\u20133 February 2008; he was also re-elected as President of the RDR for another five years. At the congress, he invited the former rebel [[Forces Nouvelles de C\u00f4te d'Ivoire|New Forces]], from whom he had previously distanced himself, to team up with the RDR for the election.<ref name=Pret>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/pays/cote_ivoire/article_depeche.asp?art_cle=AFP35428alassselleb0 \"Alassane Ouattara pr\u00eat \u00e0 s'associer aux ex-rebelles\"], AFP, 3 February 2008.</ref>\n\nAt the time, Ouattara said publicly that he did not believe Gbagbo would organize transparent and fair elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=39769 |title=\"We Don't Believe Gbagbo Will Organise Transparent Elections\" Michael Deibert interviews Alassane Ouattara |publisher=Inter Press Service |date=23 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826181445/http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=39769 |archivedate=26 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe RDR and the PDCI are both members of the Rally of Houphou\u00ebtistes, and while Ouattara and B\u00e9di\u00e9 ran separately in the first round, each agreed to support the other if only one of them made it into a potential second round.<ref name=Pret/>\n\n===2010 presidential election and aftermath===\n[[File:Alassane Ouattara UNESCO 09-2011.jpg|thumb|right|Ouattara at [[UNESCO]] in September 2011]]\n{{update|date=December 2013}}<!--http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2013/12/ivory-coast-targets-gbagbo-followers-ghana-201312252716257571.html-->\n{{main|2010 Ivorian presidential election|2010\u20132011 Ivorian crisis}}\n\nThe presidential elections that should have been organized in 2005 were postponed until November 2010. The preliminary results announced independently by the president of the Electoral Commission from the headquarters of Ouattara due to concern about fraud in that commission.{{clarify|date=February 2018}} They showed a loss for Gbagbo in favour of former prime minister Alassane Ouattara.<ref name=Thousands26>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12079552|accessdate=26 December 2010|publisher= BBC News |title= Thousands flee Ivory Coast for Liberia amid poll crisis|date=26 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe ruling FPI contested the results before the [[Constitutional Council (Ivory Coast)|Constitutional Council]], charging massive fraud in the northern departments controlled by the rebels of the New Forces. These charges were contradicted by United Nations observers (unlike African Union observers). The report of the results led to severe tension and violent incidents. The Constitutional Council, which consisted of Gbagbo supporters, declared the results of seven northern departments unlawful and that Gbagbo had won the elections with 51% of the vote \u2013 instead of Ouattara winning with 54%, as reported by the Electoral Commission.<ref name=Thousands26 /> After the inauguration of Gbagbo, Ouattara\u2014who was recognized as the winner by most countries and the United Nations\u2014organized an alternative inauguration. These events raised fears of a resurgence of the civil war; thousands of refugees fled the country.<ref name=Thousands26 />\n\nThe [[African Union]] sent [[Thabo Mbeki]], former President of South Africa, to mediate the conflict. The [[United Nations Security Council]] adopted a resolution recognising Alassane Ouattara as winner of the elections, based on the position of the [[Economic Community of West African States]], which suspended Ivory Coast from all its decision-making bodies<ref>[http://news.ecowas.int/presseshow.php?nb=188&lang=en&annee=2010 \"Final Communique on the Extraordinary Session of the Authority of Heads of State and Government on Cote D\u2019Ivoire\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503190625/http://news.ecowas.int/presseshow.php?nb=188&lang=en&annee=2010 |date=3 May 2011 }}, Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), 7 December 2010.</ref> while the African Union also suspended the country's membership.<ref>[http://www.africa-union.org/root/au/Conferences/2010/december/Communiqu%C3%A9%20of%20the%20252nd.pdf \"Communique of the 252nd Meeting of the Peace and Security Council\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206013356/http://www.africa-union.org/root/au/Conferences/2010/december/Communiqu%C3%A9%20of%20the%20252nd.pdf |date= 6 February 2011 }}, African Union, 9 December 2010.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, a colonel of the Ivory Coast armed forces, Nguessan Yao, was arrested in New York in a year-long [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] operation charged with procuring and illegal export of weapons and munitions: 4,000 [[9 mm]] handguns, 200,000 rounds of ammunition, and 50,000 tear-gas grenades, in violation of a UN embargo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/ice-deports-ivory-coast-army-colonel-convicted-arms-trafficking |date=November 30, 2012 |title=ICE deports Ivory Coast army colonel convicted of arms trafficking |publisher=Immigration and Customs Enforcement}}</ref> Several other Ivory Coast officers were released because they had diplomatic passports. His accomplice, Michael Barry Shor, an international trader, was located in [[Virginia (state)|Virginia]].<ref>[http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2010/09/21/FBI-nabbed-colonel-on-official-business/UPI-16431285082800/ \"FBI nabbed colonel on official business\"], UPI, 21 September 2010.</ref><ref>[https://cases.justia.com/federal/appellate-courts/ca9/13-10642/13-10642-2015-12-18.pdf?ts=1450472514 United States Court of Appeals Memorandum], 18 December 2015.</ref>\n\nThe 2010 presidential election led to the [[2010\u20132011 Ivorian crisis]] and the Second Ivorian Civil War. International organizations reported numerous human-rights violations by both sides. In the city of [[Du\u00e9kou\u00e9]], hundreds of people were killed. In nearby [[Blol\u00e9quin]], dozens were killed.<ref>{{cite web|date=27 April 2011|last=DiCampo|first=Peter|title= An Uncertain Future| url= http://pulitzercenter.org/articles/ivory-coast-gbagbo-election-violence|work=Ivory Coast: Elections Turn to War |publisher= Pulitzer Center}}</ref> UN and French forces took military action against Gbagbo.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/ivory-coast-strongman-arrested-after-french-forces-intervene/2011/04/11/AFOBaeKD_story.html |title= Ivory Coast strongman arrested after French forces intervene |first1= Colum |last1= Lynch |first2= William |last2= Branigin |work= [[Washington Post]] |date=11 April 2011 |accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref> Gbagbo was taken into custody after a raid into his residence on 11 April 2011. The country was severely damaged by the war, and observers say it will be a challenge for Ouattara to rebuild the economy and reunite Ivorians.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/apr/11/ivory-coast-gbagbo-ouattara-economic-crisis|title=The war is over \u2014 but Ouattara's struggle has barely begun|work= The Guardian|date=11 April 2011|first= Thalia |last= Griffiths|location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe developments in the country were welcomed by world leaders. U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] applauded news of the developments in C\u00f4te d'Ivoire and CNN quoted U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton as saying Gbagbo's capture \"sends a strong signal to dictators and tyrants.... They may not disregard the voice of their own people\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/11/ivory.coast.crisis/?hpt=T2 |title=Obama, Clinton welcome new developments |work=CNN |date=11 April 2011 |accessdate=12 April 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110412034017/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/04/11/ivory.coast.crisis/?hpt=T2| archivedate= 12 April 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==== 2012 Marriage Law row ====\nIn a controversial move in November 2012, President Ouattara sacked his government in a row over a new marriage law that would make wives joint heads of the household. His own party supported the changes but the elements of the ruling coalition resisted, with the strongest opposition coming from the Democratic Party of C\u00f4te d'Ivoire.<ref>{{Citation|title=Ouattara dissolves Ivorian government over marriage law|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20322103|year=2012|publication-place=[[United Kingdom]]|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=16 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Second term, 2015\u2013present===\n{{Main|2015 Ivorian presidential election}}\nAlassan Ouattara won a second five-year term in 2015 with almost 84% of the vote. With 2,118,229 votes, or 83.66% of votes cast, and a 54.63% turnout, Ouattara's victory was a landslide compared to the 50% required to avoid a run-off and the 9% of his closest rival, FPI leader [[Pascal Affi N'Guessan]].\n\nAt the RDR's Third Ordinary Congress on 9&ndash;10 September 2017, it was expected that Ouattara would be elected as President of the RDR, but he instead proposed [[Henriette Diabat\u00e9]] for the post, and she was duly elected by acclamation.<ref>Sylvestre-Treiner, Anna, [http://www.jeuneafrique.com/473092/politique/cote-divoire-henriette-diabate-nouvelle-presidente-du-rdr-le-parti-dalassane-ouattara/ \"C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire : Alassane Ouattara choisit Henriette Dagri Diabat\u00e9 pour pr\u00e9sider son parti\"], ''Jeune Afrique'', 10 September 2017 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n\n==== Foreign Honours ====\n\n* [[File:PRT Order of Prince Henry - Grand Collar BAR.png|alt=|80x80px]] Grand Collar of the [[Order of Prince Henry]], [[Portugal]] (September 12, 2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Africa|Biography|Politics}}\n{{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050206052408/http://alassaneouattara.com/ Alassane Ouattara.com] Political Web site from Ouattara's circle of influence.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt-Boigny]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of government of Ivory Coast|Prime Minister of the Ivory Coast]]|years=1990\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Daniel Kablan Duncan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Laurent Gbagbo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of state of Ivory Coast|President of the Ivory Coast]]|years=2010\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Goodluck Jonathan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairperson of the [[Economic Community of West African States]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Dramani Mahama]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{IvorianPresidents}}\n{{IvorianPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouattara, Alassane}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Drexel University alumni]]\n[[Category:Heads of government of Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Ivorian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Ivorian democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Ivorian economists]]\n[[Category:Ivorian people of Burkinab\u00e9 descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dimbokro]]\n[[Category:Rally of the Republicans politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Ivory Coast]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Order of Benin]]\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alassane_Ouattara"}
{"title_page": "List of current Interscope Records artists", "text_new": "{{pp-sock|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{for|artists formerly with Interscope Records|List of former Interscope Records artists}}\nThis is a list of artists who currently record for [[Interscope Records]].\n\nListed in parentheses are names of Interscope Records-affiliated labels for which the artist may be signed to.<!-- When adding new artists to this article page, categorize them alphabetically and under the letter that their last name begins with.\nFOR EXAMPLE: Gwen Stefani goes under \"S\", not \"G\". --><!-- Do not add artists solely to Geffen Records to this list. -->\n\n{{compact ToC|num=yes}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n==0\u20139==\n* [[The 1975]] (Dirty Hit/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\">{{cite web |url=https://www.interscope.com/ |title=Artists |publisher=[[Interscope Records]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[3 Doors Down]] (Interscope/Mercury)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* 5am (1865/Interscope)<ref>{{cite web|author=Brandon Robinson |url=https://respect-mag.com/2018/01/scoop-b-selects-future-young-thug-young-scooter-headline-breakfast-with-5am-a-listening-party-for-atlantas-rising-artist-5-am/ |title=Scoop B Selects: Future, Young Thug & Young Scooter Headline 'Breakfast with 5 AM', a listening party for Atlanta's Rising Artist 5 AM |publisher=respect-mag.com |date=2018-01-24 |accessdate=2018-11-20}}</ref>\n* [[5 Seconds of Summer]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* 6 Dogs ([[Benny Blanco|Mad Love]]/Interscope)<ref>{{cite web |last=Cooper |first=Duncan |url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/04/24/6-dogs-best-song-lyrics |title=6 dogs is the new hook god |work=[[The Fader]] |date=April 24, 2018 |accessdate=October 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[6lack]] (LVRN/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==A==\n* Kassi Ashton ([[MCA Nashville]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==B==\n* [[Jacob Banks]] (Darkroom/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Bas (rapper)|Bas]] ([[Dreamville Records|Dreamville]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[BB Nobre]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Billie Eilish]] (Darkroom/[[Interscope Records|Interscope]])<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Blackbear (musician)|Blackbear]] (Beartrap/Alamo/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Blackpink]] ([[YG Entertainment|YG]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Boogie (rapper)|Boogie]] ([[Shady Records|Shady]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[B\u00f8rns]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-end}}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n==C==\n* [[Cashmere Cat]] (Mad Love/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Celeste (singer)|Celeste]] (Polydor/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Cloves (singer)|Cloves]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Jon Connor]] (Aftermath/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Cozz]] (Dreamville/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Jay Critch]] (Rich Forever/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Cuco (musician)|Cuco]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==D==\n* [[DaBaby]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Daya (singer)|Daya]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Lana Del Rey]] (Polydor/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Dimelo Flow]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[DJ Snake]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Dr. Dre]] ([[Aftermath Entertainment|Aftermath]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Drama Relax]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Dreezy]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==E==\n* [[EarthGang]] (Dreamville/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Easy Life]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Billie Eilish]] (Darkroom/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Eminem]] (Shady/Aftermath/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-end}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n==G==\n* [[Selena Gomez]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Ellie Goulding]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Gryffin (DJ)|Gryffin]] (Darkroom/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Guns N' Roses]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==I==\n* [[Imagine Dragons]] (KIDinaKORNER/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==J==\n* J.I. the Prince of NY (GStarr Ent./Interscope)<ref>{{cite web |last=Cowen |first=Trace William |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8544774/ji-the-prince-of-ny-interscope-records |title=J.I. the Prince of NY Signs Deal With GStarr Ent/Interscope Records, Drops 'Love Won't Change' Video: Watch |work=Billboard |date=2019-11-25 |accessdate=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* [[JID]] (Dreamville/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Jamie N Commons]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Jay 305 (The Other Peoples Money Company/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Carly Rae Jepsen]] ([[Schoolboy Records|Schoolboy]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Jax Jones]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Jay Rock]] (Top Dawg/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-end}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n==K==\n* [[K Camp]] (RARE Sound/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[K. Flay]] (Night Street/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Leven Kali<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Michael Kiwanuka]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==L==\n* [[Lady Gaga]] (Streamline/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Kendrick Lamar]] ([[Top Dawg Entertainment|Top Dawg]]/Aftermath/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[LANY]] (Side Street/Polydor/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Ari Lennox]] (Dreamville/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Lil Durk]] (Only the Family/Alamo/Geffen)<ref>{{cite web|author=Nick Mojica |url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/07/lil-durk-signs-to-alamo-interscope-records/ |title=Lil Durk Signs To Alamo And Interscope Records |work=XXL |date=2018-07-27 |accessdate=2018-11-22}}</ref>\n* [[Lil Jon]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Lil Mosey]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Lil Poppa (Rule #1/Interscope)<ref>{{cite web|author=Trace William Cowen |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/06/lil-poppa-polo-g-eternal-living-video |title=Premiere: Lil Poppa and Polo G Team Up for New \"Eternal Living\" Video |work=Complex |date=2019-06-25 |accessdate=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* [[Louis the Child (duo)|Louis the Child]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==M==\n* [[Machine Gun Kelly (rapper)|Machine Gun Kelly]] (EST19XX/[[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (Boy Toy/[[Live Nation Entertainment|Live Nation]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Ella Mai]] (10 Summers/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Ann Marie]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Amber Mark]] (PMR/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Maroon 5]] ([[222 Records|222]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Melii (Rule #1/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Mike Will Made It]] (Eardruma/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Moneybagg Yo]] (N-Less/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Mura Masa]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[DJ Mustard|Mustard]] (10 Summers/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-end}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n==N==\n* [[No Doubt]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==O==\n* [[OneRepublic]] ([[Mosley Music Group|Mosley]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Only1Skoota<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==P==\n* [[Playboi Carti]] (AWGE/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-end}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n==R==\n* [[Rae Sremmurd]] (Eardruma/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Billy Raffoul<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Justin Rarri (Blackroom/Interscope)<ref>{{cite web|author=Jake Caramanno |url=https://www.elevatormag.com/justin-rarris-debut-project-is-one-to-remember/ |title=Justin Rarri's Debut Project Is One To Remember |work=Elevator Mag |date=2019-11-25 |accessdate=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n* [[Arin Ray]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Raye (singer)|Raye]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* Role Model (Mad Love/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n{{col-3}}\n\n==S==\n* [[Dylan Schneider]]<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Schoolboy Q]] (Top Dawg/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n* [[Sheck Wes]] (Cactus Jack/[[GOOD Music]]/Interscope)<ref name=\"artists\"/>\n*